{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3405522,"name":"Nolan Thwaits","username":"WowMuchDoge","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/ac8455/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-07-05T15:20:41.947Z","cooked":"

We use CANSparkMax encoders on the robot we are attempting to characterize. We create the SysId object run all the methods and the robot will move on either of the Quasistatic or Dynamic tests. However, once we download the logs and set everything up in SysId we get an error pop up that reads “Not enough data to run Acceleration Calculation which has a window size of 3… Please verify that your units and data is reasonable and then adjust you motion threshold, test duration, and/or window size to try to fix this issue.” I have looked over our code and all of our distance units seem reasonable and we run our tests on a carpet that is roughly 30’.

The relevant code can be found at this link GitHub - SubZero-Robotics/2024-CommandRobot at feature/characterization. The creation method for the SysId object can be found in src/main/cpp/subsystems/DriveSubsystem.cpp at line 74. The calls for quasistatic and dynamic methods can be found at src/main/cpp/RobotContainer.cpp starting at line 171.

Here are a couple log flies that we recorded logs.zip - Google Drive

Thank you in advance

I opened your two logs in AdvantageScope. FRC_20240625_232305.wpilog only has dynamic-forward test data in it, and FRC_20240625_230354.2.wpilog has no test data in it. You need one .wpilog file to contain all four test types: dynamic-forward, quasistatic-forward, dynamic-reverse, and quasistatic-reverse. The first warning box on Running the Identification Routine — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation seems to coincide with what happened here.
